description.value: A long-handled cutting tool of uncertain use: the cutting edges are on either side of the pointed tip, and only extend for about 5.0cm from the point up the length of the tool. Above the sharpened edges, the tool narrows, and then tapers gradually to a slightly convex butt. The edges of the metal all along the stem are rounded off smoothly, probably indicating that this part served as a handle, especially as the tool seems never to have been equipped with a separate handle of wood. The cutting edges have been ground sharp from both sides.

description.value: Conical tool, made of a very dark brown clay, possible discolouration due to applied substances to harden the clay after excavation.  The object is conical with several flattened and well smoothed faces from bringing the object in shape. The top is quite eroded by now, the drawing on the object card shows still a more pointed top. The base is roughly flat but quite eroded and parts being chipped off. Across the surface runs a groove that looks like the object was (secondary?) used for wedging. One of the flattened parts on the curved surface shows a decoration in form of a longer vertical line with several small lines perpendicular to the longer one running of to the right. The drawing of the object card shows a second vertical line on the right end side which is not visible on the object. The surface here is only very little eroded, it seems unlikely that the entire line has disappeared. Also the second band of decoration that was drawn is not visible on the object, although two horiz… (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Torah breast-plate; silver-gilt, in the form of a cartouches with foliate scrollwork in repoussé work. In the centre, a rectangular opening for insertion of four alternating plaques engraved in Hebrew with festival names, some in full (plaques a and b, others abbreviated (plaques c and d); a screw at the back enables them to be removed. The names are as follows:   Plaque (a), obv: Pesach (Passover); rev:  Shavuoth (Feast of Weeks, ie. Pentecost)  Plaque (b) obverse: Shabath K (? probably for Kodesh, ie. Holy Sabbath); reverse: Succoth (Harvest)  Plaque (c) obv: Shmini Atzeret (8th Day of Succoth); rev: Simchat Torah ('Rejoicing of the Law', ie the end of Succoth)  Plaque (d) obv: Yom Kippur (Day of Atonement); rev: Rosh Hashana (New Year)  Above the opening is a crown. The plate hangs from chains with suspension ring, with three pendant bells at the base. Maker's mark and assay mark on front.
